<paragraph id="177EBE19461AFF8CFF1FF919FBCB4807" blockId="35.[151,1437,1659,1956]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis id="25B5620B461AFF8CFF1FF919FE1C49D5" bold="true" box="[197,475,1736,1762]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Diagnostic characters.</emphasis>
The two dorsal setose lobes on tergite IX and lack of anal point combined with a strongly curved inferior volsella with some apically split setae, and median volsella with strong apical seta will separate the male of 
<taxonomicName id="D0C1C59A461AFF8CFE64F8C6FDA94807" box="[446,622,1815,1840]" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Nilothauma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strebulosum">
<emphasis id="25B5620B461AFF8CFE64F8C6FDA94807" box="[446,622,1815,1840]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">N. strebulosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from all other 
<taxonomicName id="D0C1C59A461AFF8CFCC4F8C6FC6F4807" box="[798,936,1815,1840]" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Nilothauma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="25B5620B461AFF8CFCC4F8C6FC6F4807" box="[798,936,1815,1840]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Nilothauma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5FDBED92461AFF8CFF1FF8ECFDA94893" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="description">
<paragraph id="177EBE19461AFF8CFF1FF8ECFE33484A" blockId="35.[151,1437,1659,1956]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis id="25B5620B461AFF8CFF1FF8ECFECC4860" bold="true" box="[197,267,1853,1879]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Male.</emphasis>
The male is described in detail by 
<bibRefCitation id="7350C3E8461AFF8CFD7EF8ECFC084860" author="Adam" box="[676,975,1853,1879]" pageId="35" pageNumber="42" refString="Adam, J. I. &amp; Saether, O. A. (2000) Paranilothauma strebulosa sp. n. from Costa Rica (Diptera: Chironomidae). In: Hoffrichter, O. (Ed.), Late 20 th Century Research on Chironomidae: An Anthology from the 13 th International Symposium on Chironomidae. Shaker Verlag, Aachen, pp. 19 - 23." type="book chapter" year="2000">
Adam and Saether (
<number id="A109AC3E461AFF8CFC5FF8ECFC014860" box="[901,966,1853,1879]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="2000.0">2000</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. Hypopygium and superior and median volsellae as in 
<figureCitation id="8FFAA29C461AFF8CFE9EF8B2FE37484A" box="[324,496,1891,1917]" captionStart="FIGURES 61 – 63" captionStartId="36.[151,274,1263,1287]" captionTargetBox="[188,1383,356,1262]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[151,1436,323,1265]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURES 61 – 63. Nilothauma strebulosum (Adam et Saether) comb. n., male. 61 — dorsal aspect of hypopygium. 62 — hypopygium with tergite IX and anal point removed, dorsal view left, ventral view right. 63 — median and superior volsella, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/186887/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Figures 
<number id="A109AC3E461AFF8CFE79F8B2FE37484A" box="[419,496,1891,1917]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" value="62.0" valueMax="63.0" valueMin="61.0">61–63</number>
</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="177EBE19461AFF8CFF1FF85BFDA94893" blockId="35.[151,1437,1659,1956]" box="[197,622,1930,1956]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis id="25B5620B461AFF8CFF1FF85BFE2B4893" bold="true" box="[197,492,1930,1956]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Female and immatures.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5FDBED92461DFF8BFF1FFF46FC574E11" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="177EBE19461DFF8BFF1FFF46FC574E11" blockId="36.[151,1436,151,294]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="25B5620B461DFF8BFF1FFF46FE864F86" bold="true" box="[197,321,151,177]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species was originally described in 
<taxonomicName id="D0C1C59A461DFF8BFCE6FF49FBC54F86" box="[828,1026,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Paranilothauma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="25B5620B461DFF8BFCE6FF49FBC54F86" box="[828,1026,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Paranilothauma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the two dorsal setose lobes on tergite IX were regarded as belonging to laterosternite IX (
<bibRefCitation id="7350C3E8461DFF8BFCE5FF6FFB824FEF" author="Adam" box="[831,1093,190,216]" pageId="36" pageNumber="42" refString="Adam, J. I. &amp; Saether, O. A. (2000) Paranilothauma strebulosa sp. n. from Costa Rica (Diptera: Chironomidae). In: Hoffrichter, O. (Ed.), Late 20 th Century Research on Chironomidae: An Anthology from the 13 th International Symposium on Chironomidae. Shaker Verlag, Aachen, pp. 19 - 23." type="book chapter" year="2000">
Adam &amp; Saether 
<number id="A109AC3E461DFF8BFBDFFF6FFB824FEF" box="[1029,1093,190,216]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The addition of several new Neotropical species with similar lobes clearly demonstrates that these lobes originate on tergite IX. 
<emphasis id="25B5620B461DFF8BFF1FFEDAFEA24E12" bold="true" box="[197,357,267,293]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is recorded only from 
<collectingCountry id="6FD6FE89461DFF8BFCD2FEDDFC4C4E11" box="[776,907,268,294]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
